This campaign is divided into 2 parts: 1- Online campaign is to provide a privacy tip a day that an average user could complete in 10 minutes or less. Tips will be shared through social media, such as Facebook and Twitter. 2- Offline Event aims to make users and makers of the web care, learn, teach and share about Online Privacy. Also we want to empower the users of the web to protect their privacy and control their digital footprint.

Take Back The Web - Benevento
Gli FSA di Benevento e il local coach, Daniele Scasciafratte, portano a Benevento l'evento sponsorizzato da Mozilla: Take Back The Web. La campagna Take Back The Web recita: "We live so much of our lives online, but we don’t always know what happens to the data we share or whose hands it ends up in. In order to have meaningful control of our online lives we have to understand our choices. You have the power to take back control of your data, but we need a community to take back the Web."
- Benevento - Benevento - Italy
Owner
Daniele Scasciafratte

MozBelajar: WebAPI (Part 1)
MozBelajar: WebAPI (Part 1)
WebAPI is a term used to refer to a suite of device compatibility and access APIs that allow Web apps and content to access device hardware (such as battery status or the device vibration hardware), as well as access to data stored on the device (such as the calendar or contacts list). In this workshop, Mozilla Rep Rizky Ariestiyansyah will teach the attendees to learn about WebAPI itself, and how to implement these webAPI in a web app.

Mozilla Fenek en Zapoteco Unificado (Protozapoteco)
Mozilla Fenek en Zapoteco Unificado (Protozapoteco)
El objetivo central del taller es comenzar un proceso de unificación de las 62 variantes que se hablan del zapoteco en México para la creación de un vocabulario zapoteco para tecnologías digitales que pueda ser útil en la localización de Firefox para Android. Las propuestas de unificación son i) utilizar términos del protozapoteco, que se considera el origen de las 62 variantes, y ii) la creación de nuevos términos a partir de un zapoteco común.

Introduction to Rust
Introduction to Rust
We will present the unique advantages of Rust compared to established systems programming languages. We will show what safety means in the context of a systems programming language. And we will see how Rust achieves these safety guarantees. At the end, we will show how these safety guarantees help you writing concurrent and parallel code.

The Internet of Things (IoT) is a system of interrelated computing devices, mechanical and digital machines, objects, animals or people that are provided with unique identifiers and the ability to transfer data over a network without requiring human-to-human or human-to-computer interaction.

2016
Documentary Screening: Code Rush
Documentary Screening: Code Rush
Code Rush is a 2000 documentary following the lives of a group of Netscape engineers in Silicon Valley. It covers Netscape's last year as an independent company, from their announcement of the Mozilla open source project until their acquisition by AOL. It particularly focuses on the last-minute rush to make the Mozilla source code ready for release by the deadline of March 31, 1998, and the impact on the engineers' lives and families as they attempt to save the company from ruin.

Introduction to WebExtensions in Mozilla Firefox
Introduction to WebExtensions in Mozilla Firefox
WebExtensions is a cross-browser system for developing browser add-ons. To a large extent, the system is compatible with the extension API supported by Google Chrome and Opera. Extensions written for these browsers will in most cases run in Mozilla Firefox or Microsoft Edge with just a few changes. The API is also fully compatible with multiprocess Firefox.

Firefox Add-ons using WebExtensions
Firefox Add-ons using WebExtensions
Firefox is drastically changing its extension system and replacing it with the Chrome-like WebExtensions. Chrome-like is an empty description for you? Perfect, Rizky will explain what WebExtensions are, why you should care about them and what to do if you have an extension for Firefox that you will have to port over. For those already familiar with the Chrome extension API, the talk will point out the differences and nuances to check when porting.

Become a Community Coordinator in Your Region!

The Mozilla Reps program is open to all Mozillians who are 18 years of age and above. Before you become a Mozilla Rep, you must follow our learning process so that you can become a good Community Coordinator in your region.

Community Coordinators are not a power structure over other Mozillians, instead they are here to help, empower and motivate other Mozillians to contribute to Mozilla projects.

There are tons of opportunities you can benefit from joining this program:

  • Access to a global community which includes people from many different countries and cultural backgrounds.
  • Direct support from Mozilla to help you empower others in your region to advance Mozilla’s goals.
  • Opportunity to help your local community grow.
  • Grow your leadership and communication skills and build networks with new people from many different countries around the globe.
  • Amplify Mozilla’s impact in your local region and functional area.

If you want to learn more about our program, you might want to connect with one of our currently active Mozilla Reps in your region, so you can learn and understand the challenges and opportunities of this program.

Find Mozilla Reps from your region

Major requirements:

  • The applicant needs to be at least 18 years old
  • The applicant needs to be active within Mozilla for at least 6 months

If you want to learn more about the Reps Program Selection Criteria please check here.

The Mozilla Reps application process involves two simple steps. Ready? Let's get started!

Thanks for your interest in making the Web better with Mozilla!
